name: XWWX "The Shrine Of Sekhmet" (Ultra Enigma) Limited Screen Print
description:
'The love of cats'

"I have loved cats since I rescued a stray tabby cat as a child, it really got quite attached to me, it even surprisingly got along with my pet parrot!

My avid interest in Egypt goes back to my childhood when my granddad told me to "go to Egypt it's beautiful, they have great fruits there!"

The idea behind the feline figurehead was to hybridise the the sphinx with the Egyptian lion goddess sekhmet together in an artistic metaphor. 

In the cats eyes sit the Eye of Horus which is an ancient symbol of protection. Like a metaphorical lighthouse watching over and spreading symbolic light.

The serpent is the vanishing point, acting as a warning not to delve beyond your understanding of the underworld.
(like a game of snakes and ladders)

The cobra in this sense acts as a shape shifting transition, between the dark hearted soulless beauty (Elvira), and the powerful sphinx sekhmet hybrid. 

In contrast to the top, the bottom half of the design is akin to the underworld (decay and regeneration in a never ending cycle).

On my way home from school I would see scarab beetles push there larvae in balls of dung, dodging the wheels of the mothers prams and pushchairs, (they seemed to lack the protection which I believe every living creature deserves). In contrast to those memories I have represented the beetle, within a position of power.The energy they transcend enforces the trance which encompasses Elvira

Elvira is awaiting in the darkness to be awaken by the right person or being but only she knows who that is .... or does she?" - XwwX 

A Limited edition (42 x 59.5 cm) hand screened three colour print. From a limited edition of 5 on 300GSM textured paper. Each print is signed and numbered by the artist and shipped in a postal tube from the XwwX creative lair in the south of England.

name: XwwX - Genesis Khan - IKE DANDY ASTROHOFF
description:
About this Artwork

A Limited edition (32 x 45 cm) giclee print. From a limited edition of 50 on 300GSM textured paper. Each print is signed and numbered by the artist and shipped in a postal tube from the XwwX creative lair in the south of England.

"The inspiration comes from an old colour pencil drawing from a portrait done about twenty years ago.
The original drawing had a character looking from left to right. I wanted to reverse it and develop it.I added the arm and hand in a similar posture to a singer from the band Killing Joke who I've always admired and whose music also inspires my art. 

The markings on the face, is inspired by tribal war paints from various primitive tribes such as the Maori tribe, south American and north American tribes . 

The colour selection I use continuously in all my work comes from my fascination with the art movement fauvism (from the French meaning:the wild beast), you could say the movement was led by the French modern artist Henri Matisse. 

Even though the design may appear hostile I wanted to contrast this with a comical look at the perception of stereotypes, I also gave it a light-hearted feel within the madness with the inclusion of a dandy's hat and flower." - Genesis Khan

GENESIS KHAN "Neptune Dandy" Limited Edition Print
description:
“I originally did a pencil drawing which would become the print you see today. The intention was to capture a 'Dandy' with an imposing, strong masculine posture with a double edged sword of being in touch with his feminine side. Examples of this femininity are the brightly coloured dress, which I took inspiration from Hindu art and philosophy. 

There's also a connection with the Carl Jung school of thought known as the 'anima' and 'animus', which stated that males have unconscious female qualities and vice versa. This is represented by the clothing and the bright colours, for example the use of red is menacing for the eyes but has connotations of make up on the nails and lips.” Genesis Khan - 2013

(A Limited edition (32 x 45 cm) giclee print. From a limited edition of 100 on 300GSM textured paper. Each print is signed and numbered by the artist and shipped in a postal tube from the XwwX creative lair in the south of England.)

name: GENESIS KHAN Grande Brix Smith Print
description:
"This is my impression of Brix inspired by a photograph which was on the back of 'Call For Escape Route' by The Fall. This was one of the first 12"'s I purchased in the 1980's , I distinctively recall the bass playing by Hanley on the record. Tracks which stood out to me were 'draygos Guilt' and 'no bulbs'.

When Brix joined the band she brought a new flamboyant edge to the band both visually and musically. I tried to capture this in the portrait. 

The colours I chose were the original colours as I thought these worked brilliantly. I tried to incorporate my own style of drawing, which is seemingly primitive whilst still capturing the beauty of Brix Smith. Whilst on paper this approach may seem rather ambitious.

I believe the end result is rather visually engaging and complimentary to Brix Smith , who gave her stamp of approval via Twitter ("it's interesting and I like the style. Xxx" - @Brixsmithstart)". - Genesis Khan, 2013

(A Limited edition (32 x 45 cm) giclee print. From a limited edition of 100 on 300GSM textured paper. Each print is signed and numbered by the artist and shipped in a postal tube from the XwwX creative lair in the south of England.)

name: GENESIS KHAN "Mark [E] Smith" Limited Edition Print
description:
"Mark e smith has been a big influence upon me culturally and musically. From an early age I’ve been interested in his home town Manchester, what it stands for, the delicti,identity and image.

 I found him to be revolutionary in his lyric writing singing style and the music made by the various musicians he's worked with, in particular Steve Hanley's bass playing. I believe it was mainly down to these two members which defined the bands sound. Furthermore his pronunciation of his vocals I found fascinating, however at times the vocals are incomprehensible!

 The main emotion I wanted to capture was just how eccentric Mark E Smith is. I wanted the portrait to hold the viewers attention in the same way that people or fans are mesmerized by him and the performance (stage presence).

 Further inspiration came from the album covers 'Perverted by Language' and 'The Wonderful and Frightening World Of The Fall and the 12" 'Creep' single which were was painted by Danish-born artist Claus Castenskiold. A particular lyric came to mind during the creative process of this design: "ours is not to look, ours is to continue the crack"! (The Fall, The Fantastic Life, 1981 )." -Genesis Khan, 2013

 (A Limited edition (32 x 45 cm) giclee print. From a limited edition of 100 on 300GSM textured paper. Each print is signed and numbered by the artist and shipped in a postal tube from the XwwX creative lair in the south of England.)
